</taxonomicName>
has been reported on rare occasions visiting flowers of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gay" authorityName="Gay" authorityYear="1846" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Viola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="portalesia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Viola portalesia</emphasis>
Gay
</taxonomicName>
in native habitats (
<bibRefCitation author="Espinoza, C. L. &amp; Murua, M. &amp; Bustamante, R. O. &amp; Marin, V. H. &amp; Medel, R." box="[535,770,958,984]" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" pagination="503 - 511" refId="ref127730" refString="Espinoza, C. L., Murua, M., Bustamante, R. O., Marin, V. H. &amp; Medel, R. (2012) Reproductive consequences off lower damage in two contrasting habitats: the case of Viola portalesia (Violaceae) in Chile. Revista Chilena de Historia Natural, 85, 503 - 511. https: // doi. org / 10.4067 / S 0716 - 078 X 2012000400012." type="journal article" year="2012">
Espinoza 
<emphasis box="[647,704,958,984]" italics="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">et al.</emphasis>
2012
</bibRefCitation>
) and in opened flowers in pine plantations (
<bibRefCitation author="Rivera-Hutinel, A. &amp; Bahamondez, A. &amp; Cuartas-Dominguez, M. &amp; Gonzalez, C." pageId="109" pageNumber="110" pagination="14 - 27" refId="ref137344" refString="Rivera-Hutinel, A., Bahamondez, A., Cuartas-Dominguez, M. &amp; Gonzalez, C. (2010) Diversidad de agentes polinizadores en paisajes antropogenicos: el caso del bosque maulino y su reemplazo con plantaciones de pino. In: Bustamante, R. O. &amp; Bachmann, P. L. (Eds.), Historia natural del bosque maulino costero: Disectando la biodiversidad en un paisaje antropogenico. Alvimpress impresores, Santiago, pp. 14 - 27." type="book chapter" year="2010">
Rivera-Hutinel 
<emphasis box="[151,208,994,1020]" italics="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">et al.</emphasis>
2010
</bibRefCitation>
). Because its habitat has been intensively fragmented by croplands, forestry and urbanization (
<bibRefCitation author="Miranda, A. &amp; Altamirano, A. &amp; Cayuela, L. &amp; Lara, A. &amp; Gonzalez, M." pageId="109" pageNumber="110" pagination="285 - 297" refId="ref134460" refString="Miranda, A., Altamirano, A., Cayuela, L., Lara, A. &amp; Gonzalez, M. (2017) Native forest loss in the Chilean biodiversity hotspot: revealing the evidence. Regional Environmental Change, 17, 285 - 297. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10113 - 016 - 1010 - 7" type="journal article" year="2017">
<collectingRegion box="[1339,1436,994,1020]" country="Venezuela" name="Miranda" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">Miranda</collectingRegion>
<emphasis box="[151,207,1030,1056]" italics="true" pageId="109" pageNumber="110">et al.</emphasis>
, 2017
</bibRefCitation>
), we applied the precautory principle.
</paragraph>
